 and legal theory, the authors examine the language of consent and how consent has ordered indigenous societies and shaped their relationships with governments. They also explore the kind of consent � the kind of attachment � that might ground political community and establish a fair relationship between indigenous and nonindigenous peoples. In doing so, they draw perspectives from indigenous relations into the heart of political theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLAW / Indigenous Peoples.2bisacsh1 aBoisselle, Andrée, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDyzenhaus, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIvison, Duncan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacleod, Colin M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMoore, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNapoleon, Val, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPromislow, Janna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRowse, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTully, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWebber, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWebber, Jeremy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077481885840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774818858423Cover